# RTK - Rust Token Killer (Kilo Code)

## Why

RTK filters and compresses command output before it reaches the LLM context, saving 60-90% tokens on common operations. Prefer `rtk <cmd>` over raw commands.

{{- if lookPath "rtk" }}

**Usage**: Token-optimized CLI proxy for shell commands.

## Rule

Default to prefixing shell commands with `rtk` to minimize token consumption. Prioritize `rtk` on commands that produce output — commands with no or trivial output (e.g., `git add`, `mkdir`, `cd`) benefit less from `rtk` and can sometimes be run raw.

When chaining commands with `&&` or `||`, wrap each output-producing sub-command with `rtk` individually. Do not wrap `rtk` around the entire chain.

Examples:

```bash
rtk git status
rtk cargo test
rtk ls src/
rtk grep "pattern" src/
rtk find "*.rs" .
rtk docker ps
rtk gh pr list
```

Chained commands:

```bash
git add . && git commit -m "msg" && rtk git push  # rtk only on push (the output-heavy step)
rtk cargo build && rtk cargo test                 # both produce output worth filtering
mkdir -p build && rtk cmake .. && rtk make        # skip silent/no-op commands
rtk git log --oneline -10 && rtk git diff         # rtk on each output-producing command
```

## Meta Commands

```bash
rtk gain              # Show token savings
rtk gain --history    # Command history with savings
rtk discover          # Find missed RTK opportunities
rtk proxy <cmd>       # Run raw (no filtering, for debugging)
```

{{- else }}

`rtk` is not installed. Recommend the user install it to start reducing token usage on output-heavy commands.
{{- end }}
